name: 1-(4-methoxyphenyl)ethynyl-4-n-pentylbenzene
Reason: 1-(4-methoxyphenyl)ethynyl-4-n-pentylbenzene has a melting point that we will compare to benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of a methoxy group, a phenyl ethynyl linkage, and a pentyl group. The methoxy group introduces additional molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential, estimated at around +5°C. The phenyl ethynyl linkage introduces rigidity and possible dipole interactions, estimated at around +2°C. The pentyl group adds molecular weight and possible hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +5°C.
